<s> RFC 2616 BNF defaults to case-insensitive for string literals: "literal" Quotation marks surround literal text.  </s>
<s> Unless stated otherwise, the text is case-insensitive.  </s>
<s> but the HTTP version string is defined as The version of an HTTP message is indicated by an HTTP-Version field in the first line of the message.  </s>
<s> HTTP-Version = "HTTP" "/" 1*DIGIT "." 1*DIGIT Note that the major and minor numbers MUST be treated as separate integers and that each MAY be incremented higher than a single digit.  </s>
<s> Thus, HTTP/2.4 is a lower version than HTTP/2.13, which in turn is lower than HTTP/12.3.  </s>
<s> Leading zeros MUST be ignored by recipients and MUST NOT be sent.  </s>
<s> Personally, I never had any intention that the "HTTP" be case-insensitive, and I am not aware of any clients that send it lowercase, nor any server  </s>
<s> that would accept it as lowercase.  </s>
<s> Doing so is a waste of cycles.  </s>
<s> So,  </s>
<s> I'd like that paragraph above to say: The version of an HTTP message is indicated by an HTTP-Version field in the first line of the message.  </s>
<s> HTTP-Version is case-sensitive.  </s>
<s> Servers would still be allowed to process it as case-insensitive under the general robustness principle, but clients are no longer given the excuse of "But it says in the standard ...".  </s>
