<s> Since the spec is written before most implementations, the spec cannot predict what is actually interoperable today, especially given that most (if not all) HTTP implementations are not compliant!  </s>
<s> More importantly, there are many things in RFC 2616 that are not interoperable today, even on a MUST level.  </s>
<s> I can see two choices: - document interoperability problems (there has been an effort to do that, like RFC 3143; most of those problems are not true RFC errata, but implementation bugs or areas that the RFC does not cover) - revise HTTP to remove whatever is not interoperable today (your proposal belongs to this category, and there are far more important things that do not interoperate; again, this is not true RFC 2616 errata, but could lead to new RFCs like "Streamlined HTTP" or "Slim HTTP" or, god forbid, "HTTP/2.0"; is there enough demand to go in this direction?)  </s>
